   "source": [
    "Visualizing the Sigmoid Function\n",
    "Logistic Regression works by computing a linear score z for each loan, then passing it through the sigmoid function sig(t) = 1/(1 + e^-t) to convert it into a probability between 0 and 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "- If z is very positiv - probability neaar 1 → model predicts Fully Paid\n",
    "- If z is very negative - probability neare 0 → model predicts Default\n",
    "- The decision boundary sits at z = 0, where probability = 0.5\n",
    "\n",
    "Why this plot now looks correct? After scaling, the z values from decision_function() are centered around 0 with a reasonable spread, producing the classic S-shaped sigmoid curve."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 147,
   "id": "ae42fe51",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# 1. Compute the decision score z for every loan in the test set\n",
    "z = model.decision_function(X_test_scaled)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Get the predicted probability of Class 1 (Fully Paid)\n",
    "probabilities = model.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:, 1]\n",
    "\n",
    "# 3. Sort by z so the sigmoid line draws smoothly left to right\n",
    "sort_idx = np.argsort(z)\n",
    "z_sorted = z[sort_idx]\n",
    "prob_sorted = probabilities[sort_idx]\n",
    "\n",
    "# 4. Plot\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plt.plot(z_sorted, prob_sorted, color='blue', linewidth=3, label='Sigmoid Probability')\n",
    "plt.scatter(z, y_test, color='red', alpha=0.1, label='Actual Loans (0=Default, 1=Paid)')\n",
    "plt.axhline(0.5, color='black', linestyle='--', label='Decision Boundary (50%)')\n",
    "plt.title('The Sigmoid Function: Mapping Loan Scores to Repayment Probability')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Combined Model Score (z)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Probability of Fully Paid (Class 1)')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
